 Conclusions: The accurate measurement of the gravity-mode period spacing provides an effective probe of the inner, g-mode cavity. The derived value of the coupling coefficient between the cavities is different for red giant branch and clump stars. This provides a probe of the hydrogen-shell burning region that surrounds the helium core. Core contraction as red giants ascend the red giant branch can be explored using the variation of the gravity-mode spacing as a function of the mean large separation. Full version of Table 1 is only available at the CDS via anonymous ftp to cdsarc.u-strasbg.fr (130.79.128.5) or via \href{http://cdsarc.u-strasbg.fr/viz-bin/qcat?J/A+A/540/A143}{http://cdsarc.u-strasbg.fr/viz-bin/qcat?J/A+A/540/A143}},
